<dl id="s14031c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us14" href="#s14031c">Oxen of the Sun: </a><a href="../../FF/unbs/s14all.htm#s14031c">sector 31(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> (reason) just at yr. elbow</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">And first with relation to the mind or understanding, it is manifest what mighty advantages fiction has over truth; and the <mark>reason is just at our elbow</mark>, because imagination can build nobler scenes, and produce more wonderful revolutions, than fortune or nature will be at expense to furnish. <small> Jonathan Swift, <a name="JSTT" href="/udra/udex.htm#JSTT"><cite title="source">Satires</cite></a> (1916) <cite>Tale of a Tub</cite>, p. 109</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Copied to <a name="s14085y" href="s14all.htm#s14085y">Sheet 14.085(y)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
